QES Multi Factor Analysis¶

This examples illustrates multi-factor analysis using analytics library. It shows the following steps:

  • Downloading data from the platform
  • Interfacing with the analytics library
  • Neutralizing the factor

  • Using different weighting schemes

    • Equi-weighted
    • Risk-parity weighting
    • Inverse-vol weighting
    • Specified weighting

  • Portfolio Optimization

Querying the data from LQuant¶

Lquant Query API allows access to several universes, factors (z-normal). The query api allows users to download data to memory and perform analytics. The data returned from lquant has three dimensions:

  1. Factors (K)
  2. Securities (N)
  3. Dates (M)

Below example show querying 10 factors for 10 years at month end frequency.

Improve the factor coverage of Analyst Expectation factors¶

Certain Analyst Expectation factors may not have reasonable coverage and history. In order to address any potential coverage and history issues, we replace those expected factors with their realized counterpart (i.e. FY0) instead of expected (i.e. FY1).

In [5]:

#Adjust Market Cap using FX Ratee

Initialize the list of factors to query¶

In [6]:
# Define Factors to load

#alpha factors are mainly used to generate excess market returns
alpha_factors = [  'EPSYLD_NTM_ADJ',     # Expected Earnings Yield in 12 months (adjusted with Actual Earnings Yield when Expected is missing)
                   'CFOYLD_FY1_ADJ',     # Expected Operating Cash flow yield, FY1 (adjusted with Actual Earnings Yield when Expected is missing)
                   'EPSYLD_NTM',
                   'CFOYLD_FY1',
                   'DEBT_ASSET',         # Total Debt / Total Assets
                   'INT_COVER',          # Interest Coverage 
                   'DEBT_EBIT',          # Debt / EBIT
                   'MERTON',             # Merton's distance to default
                   'ES_EPS_NTM_R3M',     # 3-months earnings revisions
                   'ES_SALE_NTM_R3M',    # 3-months revenue revisions
                   'REAL_VOL',           # 1-year volatility (lower is better, standard deviation of daily returns over 252 days) 
                   'RTN12M',             # 1-year trend (252-day total return  price and dividend incorporate of total return)        
          ]

#risk factors are mainly used for neutralization to remove bias and increase risk-adjusted signal's performance
risk_factors = [ 'LOG_MKTCAP_ADJ',          #Log of Market Capitalization
                 'BETA_LOCAL'           #Regression Coefficient Beta derived from QES Risk Model
               ]

all_factors = alpha_factors + risk_factors
print ("List of factors to query from LQuant:\n")
pprint(all_factors)

Initialize the parameters for Portfolio Optimization¶

In [7]:
# ============================== Optimization parameters and features =====================================#
min_adv = 1.0e7                   # Minimum Average Daily Volume ($) for the stock
                                  #The min_adv is the filtering ADV, i.e., any security that has traded less than 15 million on an average over the last 1 month is taken out of the investment universe. The definition of average ADV is (Average # of Shares Traded over the past one Month from the rebalance date) * (Current Price). 

do_optimization = True            # If set to true, it would run Optimization for the weight

OPTIMIZATION_CONTROLS = {
    'tracker' : 'EquiWeightedScore', # Other Options VolWeightedScore, RiskParityWeightedScore, SpecifiedWeightedScore
    'constraints' : {
        'neut': [],                    # Add factors for Neutralization constraint
        'hard_to_borrow': False 
    },
    'notional': 5e7, # Notional for optimization (currently set to 50 million USD)
    'max_adv':  0.1 # Max ADV constraint (currently set to 10%)
}

LQuant APIs to query factors data¶

In [8]:
univ = 'CIQMSCI_379978898'                                 # Mnemonic for MSCI World Universe: CIQMSCI_379978898
start_date = '2012-06-01'
end_date = '2022-07-01'
freq = '1me'                                               # For every month end (it can be '1d', '1w' or '1m')

wq.env().run('library(lqrisk)')
req = wq.new_request()                                     # New data request

req = req.runFor(univ)                                     # MSCI World: CIQMSCI_379978898
                                                           # Run for TQAMSCI_984000(MSCI US)
                                                           # Please use following mnemonic to load data
                                                           # MSCI World ex-US: TQAMSCI_991000 
                                                           # US: TQAMSCI_984000 
                                                           # EM: TQAMSCI_891800 
                                                        

req = req.start(start_date).to(end_date)                   # From start date to end date
req = req.at(freq)                                         # For every month end (it can be 1d, 1w or 1m)

req = req.attr(*tuple(all_factors))                        # Add all factors to data request
req = req.a('QES_COUNTRY')                                 # Or you can add one factor
req = req.a('QES_GSECTOR')                                 # Here we are adding 2 character GICS cocxe
req = req.a('COMPANYNAME')
req = req.a('SEDOL')
req = req.a('TICKER')

# This is only needed for optimizer
if do_optimization:
    req = req.a('ADV_1M_USD') # Volume is required for optimizer to work with ADV and Volume constraint
    for f1 in OPTIMIZATION_CONTROLS.get('constraints').get('neut'):
        req = req.a(f1)  

req = req.addForwardReturn()                               # Add forward return
req = req.addInFlag()                                      # Add in universe flag

data = wq.get_data(req)                                    # Execute data

factors_covg_adj = ['EPSYLD_NTM_ADJ', 'EPSYLD_NTM', 'CFOYLD_FY1_ADJ', 'CFOYLD_FY1']
factor_plot_params_map = {'EPSYLD_NTM_ADJ': [1.0, 'darkorchid'], 'EPSYLD_NTM': [0.4, 'darkorchid'], 'CFOYLD_FY1_ADJ': [1.0, 'orangered'], 'CFOYLD_FY1': [0.4, 'orangered']}

for factor in factors_covg_adj:
    df = data.element(factor).as_matrix().reset_index()

    cols = list(df.columns)[1:]
    nan_value_dict = {col: df[col].notnull().sum() for col in cols}
    factor_nan_values = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(nan_value_dict,  orient ='index').reset_index()
    factor_nan_values.columns = ['Date', 'Coverage']
    factor_nan_values['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(factor_nan_values['Date'])
    
    plt.plot(factor_nan_values['Date'], factor_nan_values['Coverage'], label = factor, alpha = factor_plot_params_map[factor][0], color = factor_plot_params_map[factor][1])

Size and Beta Neutralization of Alpha Factors using Multivariate Regression¶

Factors are the Neutralized against size and beta. This is to ensure that the factor and resulting model is not taking on too much size and beta exposure. This is accomplished regressing the normalized factor score to size and beta and then utilizing the residual as the resulting factor. Our research shows that this typically increases risk adjusted performance.

In [19]:
#Neutralize all the alpha factors against the risk factors
for ff in factors:   
    print('Neutralizing Factor ' + ff + ' against the risk factors')
    analytics.regress_multi_factor(ff, ff, risk_factors)

Multi-factor Weighting and Composite factor construction¶

We have a python class that helps with doing different weightings. Prior to weighting the factor, we neutralize the factor. Here we demonstrate 4 different types of weighting

  • Inverse Vol Weighted
  • Risk Parity Weighted
  • Equi Weighted
  • Specified Constant Weighted

1. Inverse Volatility Weighting¶

Assigns more (less) weight to factor having lower (higher) standard deviation of Rank IC. Intuitively, a factor having high variability in predicting the future returns gets less weight and vice versa.

\begin{equation} \begin{split} &\Large w_{i, t} = \frac{\frac{1}{\sigma_{i, t}}}{\sum_{j=1}^{K} \frac{1}{\sigma_{j, t}}}, \\ \\ &\large \sigma_{i, t} = Standard\ Deviation\ of\ Rank\ IC\ of\ Factor\ i \end{split} \end{equation}

We can then use these weights to compute the composites. Compute the weights using the vol weighting above. In below code, the composite is created (VolWeightedScore) using a weighted average of all the factor weights derived from Inverse Volatility Weighting.

\begin{equation} \begin{split} &\large w\_comp_{t} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{K} w_{i,t} * f_{i, t} }{\sum_{i=1}^{K} w_{i,t}} \end{split} \end{equation}

Target Variable Y¶

Encode into boolean target variable. The natural output future stock return that we try to predict is still continuous. However, there are good reasons to translate the problem from continuous to discrete. Instead of forecasting stock returns, we convert the problem to **predicting outperformers versus underperformers** - we can classify the top 30% stocks as outperformers and similarly the bottom 30% as underperformers.

There are a number of reasons why such a transformation may be more desirable:

  • The first motivation is that getting a point estimate of future stock return is extremely challenging, if not impossible. Models may overfit the data and may not be able to generalize to predict returns out-of-sample.

  • On the other hand, classification problems tend to be more robust. In addition, some investors concern about hit rate (e.g., percentage of stocks with above or below average returns) more than the average. In particular, if a managers portfolio is highly concentrated, she cant take advantage of a model with a great average return, but dominated by a few outliers.

  • More importantly, a classification- based model is naturally different from a regression framework; therefore, provides diversification benefit.

In [35]:
forward_rtn = data.element('FRTN1P').as_matrix()

def encode_target(rtn):
    """cross-sectional encoding function"""
    output_arr =  rtn.copy()
    output_arr[:] = np.NaN
    rtn_threshold = np.percentile(rtn[~np.isnan(rtn)], [30, 70])
    output_arr[rtn>rtn_threshold[1]] = 1
    output_arr[rtn<rtn_threshold[0]] = 0
    
    return output_arr

# continuous response variable
Y_rtn = forward_rtn.iloc[:,:-1]
Y_target = forward_rtn.iloc[:,:-1].apply(encode_target)

ML Feature Selection¶

  • ElasticNet linear regression uses the penalties from both LASSO and ridge techniques to regularize regression models.

    It is designed to solve the optimization of loss function by adding the following shrinkage term over the linear coefficients $\beta$:

    $$ \lambda \bigl[ \frac{1}{2} (1-\alpha) \; || \beta ||^2_2 + \alpha \; || \beta ||_1 \bigr] $$

    Due to the ridge regularization, the elastic net estimator *can handle correlations between the predictors* better than LASSO and due to the L1 regularization, *sparsity* is obtained.

  • XGBoost stands for Extreme Gradient Boosting, where the term Gradient Boosting originates from the paper Greedy Function Approximation: A Gradient Boosting Machine, by Friedman.

1. ElasticNet Feature Selection¶

  • **Elastic Net Model Hyperparameter**

    alpha: Shriankge term, defaults to 1.0. alpha = 0 is equivalent to an ordinary least square

    Please note in sklearn's elastic net, the alpha parameter argument represents the $\lambda$ shrinkage coefficeint.

    l1_ratio: The ElasticNet mixing parameter. For l1_ratio = 0 the penalty is an L2 penalty. For l1_ratio = 1 it is an L1 penalty. For 0 < l1_ratio < 1, the penalty is a combination of L1 and L2.

In [37]:

  • **XGBoost Model Hyperparameter**

    [ ] Source Link

    max_depth$d$ - *Maximum depth of a tree.* Increasing this value will make the model more complex and more likely to overfit. 0 indicates no limit on depth.

    eta$\eta$ - *Step size shrinkage used in update to prevents overfitting.* After each boosting step, we can directly get the weights of new features, and eta shrinks the feature weights to make the boosting process more conservative. By default set up tp 0.3.

    gamma $\gamma$ - *Minimum loss reduction required to make a further partition on a leaf node of the tree.* The larger gamma is, the more conservative the algorithm will be.

    subsample - *Subsample ratio of the training instances.* Setting it to 0.5 means that XGBoost would randomly sample half of the training data prior to growing trees. and this will prevent overfitting. Subsampling will occur once in every boosting iteration as a stochastic gradient descent.

Portfolio Optimization¶

There are 2 optimizers available in the LQuant environment.

QES Optimizer¶

  • The QES optimizer is a comprehensive optimizer that can handle different objective functions
    • MVO: Mean Variance Optimization
    • MRO: Mean Risk Optimization
    • maxAlpha: Maximum Alpha Optimization
    • minRisk: Minimum Risk Optimization
  • The QES Optimizer can handle arbitrary long/short constraints
  • The QES Optimizer can work with QES Risk Models as well as other risk models
  • The QES Optimizer can have integer contraints
  • The QES Optimizer can apply Neutralization constraints on Custom Factors as well as Risk Factors
  • The QES Optimizer can use either standard or custom benchmarks
  • The QES Optimizer can handle ADV constraint for both holding and trading
  • The QES Optimizer can handle Turnover constraint
  • The QES Optimizer is relatively slower than L2 Norm optimizer

L2 Norm Optimizer (Fast)¶

  • The L2 optimizer attempts to solve the weights that minimizes the L2 norm between the optimized weights and tracking weights
  • The L2 optimizer can handle turnover constraints
  • The L2 optimizer can handle hard to borrow constraints
  • The L2 optimizer can handle custom neutralization constraints
  • The L2 optimizer can handle turnover penalty
  • The L2 optimizer only works for Long/Short portfolios

### New Optimizer...
## bins not used. It is done to keep the signature consistent with the run_optimization function

def run_optimization2(name, bins):
    from lquantPy import LQOptimizer

    notional = OPTIMIZATION_CONTROLS.get('notional')
    tracker = OPTIMIZATION_CONTROLS.get('tracker')
    optimizer = LQOptimizer.QESOptimizer(template = 'default', name = 'opt', analytics = analytics)

    optimizer.set_long_short_benchmark(tracker)
    #"objective"= 'MVO', 'MVO', 'MRO', 'maxAlpha', 'minRisk'
    optimizer.set_objective('minRisk')
    
    neut_factors = OPTIMIZATION_CONTROLS.get('constraints').get('neut_risk')
    
    if neut_factors and len(neut_factors) > 0:
        optimizer.set_risk_neutralization_factor(neut_factors, 
                                             factor_min_exposure = -0.05, factor_max_exposure = 0.05)
    optimizer.set_max_long_weight(1)
    optimizer.set_min_long_weight(1)
    optimizer.set_max_short_weight(1)
    optimizer.set_min_short_weight(1)
    optimizer.set_bounds(lb = -0.2, ub = 0.2)
    optimizer.set_notional_value(notional,notional)
    #optimizer.set_max_ADV_holding_participation(0.4)
    #optimizer.set_max_ADV_trading_participation(0.4)
    optimizer.set_adv_factor('ADV_1M_USD')
    optimizer.set_use_tcm(False)
    optimizer.summarize()
    
    if OPTIMIZATION_CONTROLS.get('constraints').get('hard_to_borrow'):
        optimizer.set_htb_threshold(1.0)

    
    if len(optimizer.msg()) > 0:
        print('Optimization failed due to ==> ' + optimizer.msg())
        return False
    
    optimizer.submit()

    optimizer.wait(3600)
    
    info = optimizer.info()
    status = info['status'].as_string()
    
    if status != 'SUCCESS':
        print('Optimization failed due to ==> ' + info['message'])
        return False
    
    optResult = optimizer.get_data()
    
    if optResult.is_error():
        print('Optimization failed due for date ==> ' + optResult.failed_date())
        return False
    
    optResult.append_weight_to_data(name)
    
    breq = wq.new_backtest_request()
    breq.forFactor(tracker)
    breq.weightFactor(name)
    opt_performance = wq.basic_backtest(data = data, req = breq)
    # Append to backtest_results
    backtest_results.backtest_results = backtest_results.backtest_results + [opt_performance]
    backtest_results.factors = backtest_results.factors + [name]
    return True

Wolfe L2 Norm Optimizer¶

  • **Objective:** To track weights provided by factor score. The tracking is done using simple L2 minimization technique. Note that it does not use any risk model.
\begin{equation} \begin{split} \large Minimize\ \phi_{t} = \sum_{i=1}^{N} (w_{i, t} - x_{i,t})^2 \end{split} \end{equation}
  • **Weighting methodology:** Signal Weighted (The weight is proportional to signal) and Long Short Equal Weighted with Tercile, Quartile, Quintile etc.
  • **Turnover constraint:** The penalty function is added to the object function
\begin{equation} \begin{split} \large Turnover Penalty\ = \sum_{i=1}^{N} (w_{i, t} - w_{i,t-1})^2 \end{split} \end{equation}
  • **Max Weight:** Each security weight is constrained to be less than specified weight
\begin{equation} \begin{split} \large |w_{i,t}| < Max\ Weight\ \forall\ i \in (1, N) \end{split} \end{equation}
  • **ADV Constraint:** Weight of each security is constrained such that the final portfolio does not contain notional value greater than some fraction of daily average volume
\begin{equation} \begin{split} \large |w_{i,t}| < \frac{ADV_{i}}{Notional} \forall\ i \in (1, N) \end{split} \end{equation}

    breq.withBins(NUM_BINS)

    backtest_results.factors = backtest_results.factors + [name]

def run_optimization(name, bins, turnover_penalty = None):
    try:
        portfolio_build_request = wq.new_portfolio_request(OPTIMIZATION_CONTROLS.get('notional')) ### 50,000,000 Notional

        # Build signal weighted portfolio
        portfolio_build_request = portfolio_build_request.factorWeight(OPTIMIZATION_CONTROLS.get('tracker'), 
                                                                       bins)

        # Set max weight to 10%
        portfolio_build_request = portfolio_build_request.maxWeight(0.2)

        # Set borrow cost constraint Anything that has score > 1.0

        if OPTIMIZATION_CONTROLS.get('constraints').get('hard_to_borrow'):
            portfolio_build_request = portfolio_build_request.filterHardToBorrow(1.0)
        else:
            portfolio_build_request = portfolio_build_request.filterHardToBorrow(0.0)

        # Neutralize the Momentum factor
        neut_factors = OPTIMIZATION_CONTROLS.get('constraints').get('neut')
        if len(neut_factors) > 0:
            portfolio_build_request = portfolio_build_request.neutFactors(neut_factors)
            #portfolio_build_request = portfolio_build_request.neutFactors(['RTN_12M1M'])

        # Ensur that sector are neutralized
        #portfolio_build_request.neutSector(['QES_GSECTOR'])

        # Stock should trade at least $1M USD based on 1 month average trading volume
        #portfolio_build_request = portfolio_build_request.minAdv(1e7) ## Minimum ADV to be included

        # Max ADV Participation to 4% 
        #portfolio_build_request = portfolio_build_request.maxADV(0.10);
        
        # Max ADV Participation
        adv_limit = OPTIMIZATION_CONTROLS.get('max_adv')
        if adv_limit:
            portfolio_build_request = portfolio_build_request.maxADV(adv_limit);

        # Add 5% turnover penalty to reduce turnover. With 100% turnover penalty the builder with 
        # try to minimize turnover
        
        if turnover_penalty:
            portfolio_build_request = portfolio_build_request.turnoverPenalty(turnover_penalty)

        # Add 5% turnover penalty to reduce turnover. With 100% turnover penalty the builder with 
        # try to minimize turnover
        #portfolio_build_request = portfolio_build_request.turnoverPenalty(0.005)
        print ("Starting Optimization.." + name)
        wq.build_portfolio(data = data, req = portfolio_build_request)
        print ("Optimization Successful " + name)
        
        wq.env().run("{}[['{}']]<-{}[['{}']]".format(data.name(),name,data.name(),'OPT_WEIGHT'))
        wq.env().run("{}[['{}']]<-NULL".format(data.name(),'OPT_WEIGHT'))

        breq = wq.new_backtest_request()
        breq.forFactor(OPTIMIZATION_CONTROLS.get('tracker'))
        breq.weightFactor(name)
        opt_performance = wq.basic_backtest(data = data, req = breq)
        # Append to backtest_results
        backtest_results.backtest_results = backtest_results.backtest_results + [opt_performance]
        backtest_results.factors = backtest_results.factors + [name]
        wq.env().run("mode({}[['IN']])<-'numeric'".format(data.name()))
        return True
    except Exception as e:
        print(e)
        return False

Generate Excel File with Factor Statistics¶

Backtest result class provides a simple function to generate an Excel with key metrics of the backtesting in once place

  • Coverage (Aggregate and over Time)
  • Long/Short Performance
  • Turnover (Average and over Time)
  • CAGR (Several Period)
  • Sharpe Ratio
  • IC
In [ ]:
# Arg1: Name of the Universe
# Arg2: Number of baskets in the backtest
backtest_results.generate_excel('MSCI-World_All-Factors_20220708',NUM_BINS)
#backtest_results_aggr.generate_excel('MSCI-World_Aggregate-Factors_20220704',NUM_BINS)

The above code will generate a file at the current working directory

  • Backtest_Stats_MSCI US Index_5_M.xlsx The file can be downloaded by going to Jupyter home directory and clicking on this file.

Access Backtest Metrics from the Results object¶

In [ ]:
# Below function is getting the first backtest object and outputting the wealth curves for each quintile and long/short 
# basket
print('Quintile Wealth Curve Long/Short Vol Weighted Baskets')
backtest_results.get(0).wealth().as_matrix()

Other Available Functions¶

  • serial_correlation
    • Provides serial correlation
    • Example:
      • backtest_results.get(0).serial_correlation().as_double_array()
  • turnover
    • Provide turnover as percentage of one-side notional.
    • Example:
      • print(backtest_results.get(0).turnover().names())
      • backtest_results.get(0).turnover().as_double_array()
  • basket_returns
    • Provides long/short basket period returns
    • Example:
      • backtest_results.get(0).basket_returns().as_double_array()
  • volatility
    • Provides overall volalility of the each quintile basket and long
    • Example:
      • print(backtest_results.get(0).volatility().names())
      • backtest_results.get(0).volatility().as_double_array()

While users can use matplotlib or plotly to visualize results, they can also use built graphs that can be invoked by Image function of Jupyter.
